If the mouse events are generated by Qt itself, then you can do this in your `main()` function:
   

    QApplication::setAttribute(Qt::AA_SynthesizeMouseForUnhandledTabletEvents, false);

There are some other similar attributes like the above:
	

    QApplication::setAttribute(Qt::AA_SynthesizeMouseForUnhandledTouchEvents, false);
    QApplication::setAttribute(Qt::AA_SynthesizeTouchForUnhandledMouseEvents, false);

But if the mouse events are generated by the operating system (Windows does that), then you need too live with them, and filter out the mouse events by `source()`:

    void YourWidget::mousePressEvent(QMouseEvent *event)
    {
    	if(event-&gt;source() == Qt::MouseEventNotSynthesized) {
    		// it is a real mouse event!
    	}
    	event-&gt;accept();
    }

